  "reference_solution": {
    "python": "import sys\n\ndef main():\n    data = sys.stdin.read().split()\n    pos = 0\n    t = int(data[pos]); pos += 1\n    out = []\n    for _ in range(t):\n        word, k = data[pos], int(data[pos + 1]) % 26; pos += 2\n        out.append(\"\".join(chr((ord(c) - 97 - k) % 26 + 97) for c in word))\n    sys.stdout.write(\"\\n\".join(out) + \"\\n\")\n\nmain()\n"
  },
  "hints": [
    "Sliding a letter back 26 times lands it exactly where it started. What does that tell you about a giant K like 10^9?",
    "Only K modulo 26 matters. For each letter, take its position 0–25, subtract K mod 26, add 26, and take mod 26 again — that is the original position. Pure arithmetic, no repeated stepping."
